{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532167"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:23:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:23:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14655"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14655"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.2,0.25,0.02,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111358"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7348"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93488"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"172"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"},{"type":"tags","id":"1325"},{"type":"tags","id":"1654"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3836"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45326"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111358"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of progressive lower back pain and worsening leg weakness. She has a medical history of metastatic breast cancer with known spinal metastases and is receiving palliative chemotherapy. Since yesterday she has had difficulty initiating urination with several episodes of urinary incontinence. Her regular medications are paracetamol, oxycodone, and anastrozole. She does not smoke and lives with her partner. She has not travelled recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals reduced power at 3/5 in both lower limbs, absent ankle reflexes bilaterally, and reduced sensation in the perianal region. Digital rectal examination reveals reduced anal tone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent whole-spine magnetic resonance imaging","Immediate neurosurgical discussion","Urinary catheter insertion","Urgent computed tomography lumbosacral spine","Urgent intravenous dexamethasone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMalignant spinal cord compression is an oncological emergency. Oedema at the compression site contributes to neurological compromise; prompt corticosteroid therapy reduces vasogenic oedema and may preserve function while definitive imaging and specialist input are arranged. In a person with spinal metastases who develops bilateral leg weakness, bladder dysfunction, reduced perianal sensation, and reduced anal tone, malignant cord or cauda equina compression is highly likely, and time-critical action is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent intravenous dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial step because it can be administered immediately to reduce cord oedema and limit ongoing neurological injury. Treatment should not be delayed pending imaging or specialist advice when malignant spinal cord compression is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent whole-spine magnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is essential to confirm the level(s) of compression and to guide radiotherapy or surgical planning, but it should follow immediate steroid administration. Delaying steroids until after imaging risks avoidable deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate neurosurgical discussion\u003C/strong\u003E is important early to expeditiously plan decompression versus radiotherapy, but it should occur after initiating steroids; decisions depend on imaging findings, prognosis, performance status, and patient goals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary catheter insertion\u003C/strong\u003E may be needed to manage retention and incontinence, but it does not treat the cause of neurological compromise and should not precede time-critical steroid therapy aimed at preventing further deficit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent computed tomography lumbosacral spine\u003C/strong\u003E is faster and more available than magnetic resonance imaging in some centres, but it is less sensitive for epidural disease and does not change the immediate need for steroid therapy. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early recognition of cauda equina syndrome in people with cancer is crucial as urgent intervention may prevent permanent neurological deficit.","Dexamethasone is the initial treatment of choice for malignant spinal cord compression while arranging urgent magnetic resonance imaging.","Red flag symptoms such as bladder or bowel dysfunction and saddle anaesthesia should prompt immediate medical assessment."],"references":["Al-Qurainy R, Collis E. Metastatic spinal cord compression: diagnosis and management. Bmj. 2016 May 19;353. Available online at ; https://swastcpd.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/Metastatic-spinal-cord-compression-BMJ-article-2016.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93488"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14655"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93488"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T11:32:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T11:36:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7348"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111358"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":nu